Git Repository Creation

>> When it comes to creating a new Git repository, there are two main options 1. New Repository 2. Import Repositary


Using the GIT

1. Connect to the Project and Clone the Repository

First, connect to your project and clone the repository to your local environment.
From the screen below, ensure that your repository is located in the correct directory. If it’s not, configure the path to your preferred location.
Once everything is set, click Clone to start the process.

2. Create Branch/es

From the drop-down list, select the New Branch option.
Enter a name for your branch and click the Create button.
If you’ve selected the Checkout branch option (like I have), it will switch to the newly created branch, create it, and restore the necessary files.

3. Push the New Branch

After creating the new branch, push it to the remote repository to make it available for others.
Ensure that the branch is selected, then use the Push option to upload it to your remote Git repository.

4. Create Symbolic Link to Your Packages Local Directory

Open Command Prompt.
Navigate to the K:\AOSServices\PackagesLocalDirectory folder.
Run the following command to create the symbolic link. "mklink /d <PathToPackagesLocalDirectory> <PathToGitFolder>"
You’ll need to repeat this process for each of your models individually.
